  <br>
  <h1><i>HISTORY OF CIRCKET</i></h1>
<br>
<h3>1. Origins of Cricket (Pre-16th Century)</h3>
<br>
<em>Cricket is believed to have originated in south-east England during the late medieval period, possibly as early as the 13th century.

It was likely played by children in farming communities using shepherd’s crooks and balls made of wool or leather.

The word "cricket" may have derived from:

Middle Dutch krick(-e) (stick),

Old English cryce (crutch or staff).</em>
<br>
<h3>2. Cricket in the 16th and 17th Centuries</h3>
<br>
<em>2.1 Earliest Written Record
The first definite reference to cricket dates back to 1598 in a legal document referencing a sport called creckett played by schoolboys in Surrey around 1550.

2.2 Adult Participation
By the early 17th century, cricket had become an adult sport.

It was associated with betting, leading to the growth of more organized and competitive matches.</em>
<br>
<h3>3. 18th Century: The Birth of Professional Cricket</h3>
<br>
<em>3.1 Formation of Cricket Clubs
The first major cricket club, Hambledon Club, was established in the 1760s.

It laid down many foundations of modern cricket.

3.2 Laws of Cricket
1744: The first known codification of the Laws of Cricket.

1788: The Marylebone Cricket Club (MCC) was founded and became the guardian of the Laws.

3.3 Popularity and Patronage
Cricket gained popularity among the British aristocracy.

Wealthy patrons hired professional players, contributing to the game’s growth.</em>
<br>
<h3>4. 19th Century: Expansion and Globalization</h3>
<br>
<em>4.1 County Cricket and Domestic Growth
County cricket in England took formal shape in the 1800s.

Sussex County Cricket Club was formed in 1839, the first official county club.

4.2 Technological Developments
Round-arm bowling was legalized in 1835, and over-arm bowling in 1864.

Pitches improved, and protective gear like pads and gloves were introduced.

4.3 Cricket Goes Global
Spread through the British Empire:

India, Australia, South Africa, New Zealand, West Indies, and others began playing.

First international match: USA vs Canada in 1844.

First official Test Match: England vs Australia in 1877.</em>
<br>
<h3>5. 20th Century: The Golden Era of International Cricket</h3>
<br>
<em>5.1 Test Cricket Dominance
Test cricket was the dominant format, with series like The Ashes gaining fame.

Countries like India (1932), Pakistan (1952), and Sri Lanka (1982) entered the Test arena.

5.2 Introduction of Limited-Overs Cricket
First List A (one-day) match in 1963.

First One Day International (ODI): England vs Australia, 1971.

5.3 World Cups
First Cricket World Cup: 1975, organized by ICC in England.

India's 1983 victory marked a turning point, popularizing the game in the subcontinent.

5.4 Rise of Great Players
Legends like Don Bradman, Sunil Gavaskar, Kapil Dev, Imran Khan, Richard Hadlee, and Viv Richards emerged.</em>
<br>
<h3>6. 21st Century: Commercialization and T20 Revolution</h3>
<br>
<em>Introduction of T20 Cricket
First T20 international: 2005 between Australia and New Zealand.

First T20 World Cup: 2007, won by India.

6.2 Rise of Franchise Cricket
Indian Premier League (IPL) launched in 2008.

Other leagues followed: Big Bash (Australia), CPL (Caribbean), PSL (Pakistan), The Hundred (England).

6.3 Technological Advancements
Use of DRS (Decision Review System), Hawk-Eye, Snickometer, and LED bails.

Broadcast and streaming revolutionized fan engagement.

6.4 Expansion of Women's Cricket
Significant growth and recognition, with the ICC Women’s World Cup and T20 World Cup gaining global viewership.

Stars like Mithali Raj, Meg Lanning, Ellyse Perry, and Smriti Mandhana have risen.</em>
<br>
<h3>7. Cricket Today</h3>
<br>
<em>7.1 Governing Bodies
The International Cricket Council (ICC) oversees the sport globally.

Each country has its own cricket board (e.g., BCCI for India, ECB for England).

7.2 Formats
Three main formats: Test, One-Day (50 overs), and T20.

Innovations like T10 cricket and The Hundred continue to evolve the sport.

7.3 Global Competitions
ICC World Cups, Champions Trophy, World Test Championship, and T20 World Cup.

Cricket is set to feature in the Olympics (Los Angeles 2028).</em>
<br>
